```java
public String getDescription() {
    if (_desc == null) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();

        if (_from == null) {
            sb.append("UNKNOWN");
        } else {
            Class<?> cls = (_from instanceof Class<?>) ? (Class<?>)_from : _from.getClass();
            // Use canonical name for arrays and inner classes,
            // fall back to getName() for anonymous classes.
            String name = cls.getCanonicalName();
            if (name == null) {
                name = cls.getName();
            }
            sb.append(name);
        }
        sb.append('[');
        if (_fieldName != null) {
            sb.append('"');
            sb.append(_fieldName);
            sb.append('"');
        } else if (_index >= 0) {
            sb.append(_index);
        } else {
            sb.append('?');
        }
        sb.append(']');
        _desc = sb.toString();
    }
    return _desc;
}
```

But we need to ensure that for arrays, the canonical name is used and not the ugly name. This should work.

However, note that the original code attempted to strip the package and then add it back. That was to avoid fully qualified name? Actually, they wanted to include package name. So using `getCanonicalName()` includes package, which is fine.

